[normal]The Crown Estate welcomes the opportunity to 
[normal]respond to this 
[normal]inquiry
[normal] on the 
[normal]extractive industries sector
[normal]. 
[normal]The statements contained in this 
[normal]response
[normal] are
[normal] grounded
[normal] in The Crown Estate’s 
[normal]interests, land ownership and as largest minerals landlord of the UK
[normal]. 
[normal]The Crown Estate is a 
[normal]commercially-run, 
[normal]total return
[normal],
[normal] active asset management business
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]oversee
[normal]ing
[normal] 
[normal]a UK-wide
[normal] portfolio of
[normal] prime urban, rural
[normal], coastal
[normal] and 
[normal]offshore 
[normal]property. In line with our core values, we actively manage these to deliver a c
[normal]ommercial return, which is paid each year to the Treasury for the benefit of the nation. We 
[normal]are committed to 
[normal]careful 
[normal]stewa
[normal]rdship of the assets we have been trusted to manage.
[normal] 
[normal]The Crown Estate is g
[normal]ov
[normal]erned by an Act of Parliament, T
[normal]he Crown Estate Act 1961
[normal]. I
[normal]t has a public remit whilst at the same time being independent from Government – a statutory corporation
[normal],
[normal] run on a comme
[normal]rcial basis.
[normal] 
[normal]We are committed to working with government departments, stakeholders and industry in helping to manage the coastal and marine environment
[normal], in line with our commercial remit
[normal].
[normal]Our rural and marine assets 
[normal]comprise
[normal]:
[normal] 
[normal]As with Mines Royal, we are not involved in the physical process of mining, but we license 
[normal]such activity. In recent years we have invested in new operations with the purchase of mineral interests at Cauldon Low in Staffordshire and Nether Murthat in Scotland.
[normal] Our responsibility for Mines Royal determines the need for o
[normal]ur permission to remove Cro
[normal]wn gold in any form. We currently have four Mines Royal production leases, including one active gold mine in Northern Ireland.
[normal]With these interests combined, this makes The Crown Estate the largest minerals landlord in the UK. 
[normal]It is important to be clear t
[normal]hat The Crown Estate has no rights over UK hydrocarbons, such as Shale Gas, which accrue to ‘the Crown’ but are vested in the Department for Energy and Climate Change. In this context we are no different to any other landowner. 
[normal]Having reviewed the 
[normal]questio
[normal]ns posed in the 
[normal]inquiry
[normal], 
[normal]we have addressed 
[normal]only 
[normal]some 
[normal]of the 
[normal]specific 
[normal]questions 
[normal]with
[normal] relevance to our role
[normal]. We believe other organisations such as the Minerals Producers Association
[normal] (MPA)
[normal] and CBI Minerals Group are best placed to comment in other areas.
