[normal]Qu[bold]estion [bold]1[bold]:[bold]  What is the contribution to the UK economy of extractive industries in the UK?[bold]It is important at the outset to recognise the 
[normal]role
[normal] and impact
[normal] that terrestrial planning policy has on 
[normal]marine minerals
[normal]. This is particularly true in areas where 
[normal]land 
[normal]based
[normal] minerals are under local 
[normal]planning pressures
[normal] which restricts supply
[normal],
[normal] allowing m
[normal]arine minerals
[normal] a greater market share.
[normal] 
[normal]It is therefore very important to e
[normal]nsu
[normal]re
[normal] 
[normal]that terrestrial 
[normal]planning policy specifically references consideration of marine 
[normal]minerals as
[normal] way of
[normal] maximising the potential of this indigenous resource.
[normal]W
[normal]hilst minerals guidance is set out under the National Planning Policy Framework, with local aggregates assessments undertaken by Local Authorities, consideration of other sources, such as marin
[normal]e minerals (which are outside of 
[normal]the 
[normal]spatial demarcation
[normal] of a Local Authority)
[normal] is needed as part of broader supply chain considerations. 
[normal]C
[normal]lear policy guidance 
[normal]ensuring 
[normal]that 
[normal]marine minerals
[normal] contribution continues
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]in the context of UK supply of minerals, 
[normal]th
[normal]is 
[normal]will
[normal] maximise 
[normal]the overall
[normal] benefit
[normal] to the UK economy
[normal].
[normal]A robust regulatory regime exists
[normal] for marine aggregates
[normal], which is managed through the Marin
[normal]e
[normal] Management Organisation
[normal] 
[normal](MMO) 
[normal](England)
[normal] and
[normal] Natural Resources Wales (Wales)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] There is currently no extraction in Scottish or Northern Irish waters.
[normal] Operating businesses in this sector have a significant capital asset base to maintain, requiring security of mineral reserves
[normal], and it is 
[normal]important that the 
[normal]Marine Licence 
[normal]application p
[normal]rocedure
[normal] recognises the long term nature 
[normal]and scale 
[normal]of the associated investment profile
[normal] without 
[normal]introducing an excessive burden on the 
[normal]industry
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]The Crown Estate has introduced a procedure designed to optimise the use of the seabed whilst working within 
[normal]the guidelines introduced by the marine planning process that is currently being developed by the MMO. This procedure is also designed to provide a safeguarding protocol for key resources.
[normal]The 
[normal]MPA
[normal] recently commissioned 
[normal]a study
[normal] to assess the contribution the mineral products sector (pr
[normal]incipally minerals extracted to
[normal] supply the 
[normal]construction sector) makes to 
[normal]the UK economy
[normal] and would be able to provide conclusions outlining the Gross Value Added (GVA) contribution the sector makes 
[normal]to the UK economy.
[normal]Alongside the economic contribution minerals production makes to the UK, it is also important to recognise the need for 
[normal]a 
[normal]secure supply
[normal] of minerals for the construction industry
[normal].
[normal] Millions of tons of marine sand and gravel are used across the construction industry and for coastal management and land reclamation each year. 
[normal]The Crown Estate licens
[normal]es nearly all marine seabed sand and gravel resourc
[normal]es lying offshore around the UK
[normal];
[normal] and
[normal] has 
[normal]been licensing the activity 
[normal]for 
[normal]over 50 years
[normal]. 
[normal]Extraction of about 20 million tonnes p
[normal]er 
[normal]a
[normal]nnum
[normal] of marine aggregates 
[normal]occurs 
[normal]off the
[normal] coast of England and Wales.
[normal]As set out in the Marine Policy Statement
[normal] for the UK, m
[normal]arine mineral from UK seabed is v
[normal]iew
[normal]ed as a world class resource.
[normal] It is an important source for security of supply and there is always the potential opportunity to export our dredged materials to other countries in Europe
[normal].
[normal]As we adapt to cl
[normal]imate change, large volumes of 
[normal]marine sand and grave
[normal]ls are used in beach replenishment schemes. Aggregates are pumped directly from dredgers onto beaches,
[normal] providing coastal protection, 
[normal]e
[normal]nhancing the amenity value and 
[normal]providing security to the local economy, for example on the coast of Lincolnshire.
[normal]In addit
[normal]ion, marine sands are used in land reclamation schemes, infilli
[normal]ng areas in ports and harbours 
[normal]to reclaim land from the sea. Recent examples of reclamation include the runway extension at Ronaldsway airport on The Isle of Man and the London Gateway port dev
[normal]elopment
[normal]. 
[normal]It is important to note here that sourcing of marine based minerals ensure that the schemes undertaken are 
[normal]economically viable 
[normal]and it is likely that without these vital resource
[normal]s
[normal],
[normal] this would not be the case. 
[normal]Marine sourced mineral is unique in te
[normal]rms of the ability to import and place large quantities of mineral in a short space of time without the need for importation by road.
[normal] 
[normal]The Crown Estate is 
[normal]also 
[normal]responsible for leasing extraction of minerals lying below the UK sea bed, including deposits of
[normal] potash.
[normal] 
[normal]Potash is a generic term for a variety of potassium bearing minerals; in part
[normal]icular it is Sylvinite that is
[normal] currently
[normal] 
[normal]mined in the UK. Around 90 per cent of UK potash is used in the production of fertiliser with the remainder being used in the che
[normal]mical 
[normal]and pharmaceutical industries. 
[normal]Approximately 60 per cent of all UK production is exported each year.
[normal] 
[normal]The Boulby potash mine, situated on the North Yorkshire coast, is the UK's only commercial potash mine and the most important non-hydrocarbon minera
[normal]l operation in Britain. The mine, which started production in 1973 and is currently managed by Cleveland Potash Ltd, employs 
[normal]around
[normal] 
[normal]1100 workers (another 200 workers 
[normal]have been recruited 
[normal]this year, some of 
[normal]which
[normal] have come from closed coal mi
[normal]nes). Mining ope
[normal]rations extend 
[normal]aro
[normal]und 8 km offshore and 
[normal]the mine
[normal] is the s
[normal]econd deepest in Europe (approx
[normal]imately
[normal] 1km below sea level).
[normal]Boulby mine
[normal] produces in the order of 3 million tonnes per annum (mtpa) potash ore and refines this into 1mtpa potash mainly used in the fe
[normal]r
[normal]tiliser industry. Although the c
[normal]ompany produces enough potash to satisfy the UK demand, 
[normal]they supply about half of the UK
[normal] market with the remainder being imported from 
[normal]overseas
[normal].  
[normal]The
[normal] rock salt
[normal] also mined
[normal] 
[normal](in order to access the potash ore) is mostly sold t
[normal]o Local A
[normal]uthorities and
[normal] the Highway A
[normal]uthorities
[normal] (with 
[normal]produc
[normal]tion in the order of
[normal] about 0.8 mtpa
[normal])
[normal] as de-icing salt
[normal] for roads
[normal]. 
[normal]The Company contributes £225M per year of economic activity as measured by product sales.  They support many local small suppliers
[normal] and service companies.  Half their sales are overseas with approximate foreign earnings of £100M per year.
[normal]During 2011, York Potash 
[normal]signed an agreement with us for the rights to explore f
[normal]or polyhalite under the seabed 
[normal]to the south of Boulby and exploratio
[normal]n is underway. 
[normal]York Potash has determined 
[normal]the existence of considerable reserves
[normal] both under the land and under the seabed, and is in the process of carrying out resear
[normal]c
[normal]h to support an 
[normal]application to
[normal] 
[normal]North York Moors National Park 
[normal]for land based mining oper
[normal]ations and associated surface workings
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]A decision is expected in 2014
[normal]. 
[normal]The MMO has already 
[normal]granted
[normal] 
[normal]permission for the offshore element.
[normal]Question [bold]2[bold]:[bold]  How do the UK-based extractive industries support employment a) in the UK and b) for UK citizens overseas?[bold]Whilst The Crown Estate has previously commissioned and published work related to the analysis of socio economic indicators of marine related activ
[normal]ities in the UK economy (ISBN978-1-906410-01-8), 
[normal]the MPA have information available regarding the role the extractive industries more broadly play in supporting employment
[normal], as highlighted in our response to question 1
[normal]. 
[normal]We estimate that t
[normal]here are approximat
[normal]ely 3,000 people 
[normal]directly 
[normal]employed in the extraction
[normal] and processing
[normal] of marine minerals (
[normal]marine 
[normal]aggregates and potash)
[normal], with many more jobs involved indirectly through downstream and upstream activities.
