[normal]Question [bold]6[bold]:[bold]  Is there sufficient engagement between [bold]UK extractive industries and the NGO sector? Are there examples of best practice in engagement between the extractive industries and NGOs?[bold]The Crown Estate has sought to 
[normal]further develop 
[normal]our relationship
[normal]s
[normal] with non-governmental organisations (NGOs) with resp
[normal]ect to the activities that we lease and license. We feel that as our role has become more proactive in the development of our portfolios of activities and management of 
[normal]the 
[normal]estate, so too has the improvement in the relationship with relevant NGOs.
[normal]The Crow
[normal]n Estate funds and supports the Seabed Users and Developers Group (SUDG). The SUDG is an informal grouping of industry sectors whose participants have a common interest in sustainable development within the UK’s marine environment. The Crown Estate works w
[normal]ith SUDG to align seabed user groups across the UK to work positively with Government to prepare shared understanding and approaches to marine management. Organisations involved include sectors whose members require marine licenses for construction and ope
[normal]ration include British Ports Association, United Kingdom Major Ports Association, British Marine Aggregates Producers Association
[normal] (the minerals trade association)
[normal], British Marine Federation, Oil &amp; Gas UK, Renewable Energy Association, Renewable UK, Subsea 
[normal]Cables UK and Carbon Capture and Storage Association. 
[normal]In October 2012, SUDG published a joint statement
[normal] with 
[normal]the Marine Conservation Society, RSPB, The Wildlife Trusts and WWF to work collaboratively on marine conservation in relation to seabed uses. 
[normal]The
[normal] SUDG positively engages with environmental NGOs through this forum.
[normal]The Crown Estate also works very closely with BMAPA to develop best practice and enhance knowledge and understanding of the sector. 
[normal]We have commissioned studies in a number of areas, whic
[normal]h have been published and placed in the public domain. 
[normal]An example of these joint initiatives is “The Area Involved” reports. These are published annually as a result of a March 1999 statement of intent between The Crown Estate and BMAPA committing to revi
[normal]ewing all dredging licences over a rolling five year period. Included was a commitment to surrender areas no longer containing useful resources of sand and gravel and to publish an annual report detailing the extent of dredging within the licensed areas. T
[normal]his year’s report which is to be published shortly is the 15th in the on-going series, and has drawn widespread acknowledgement for the level of information and transparency provided.
[normal]Another example of work undertaken to 
[normal]highlight the sustainable credenti
[normal]als of the marine aggregates sector
[normal] is our involvement in
[normal] developing an industry protocol for the reporting of marine archaeology, and we provide annual analysis of the area of seabed affected by marine mineral extraction. Much of this information is available through our web site (
[normal]http://www.thecrownestate.co.uk/energy-infrastructure/research/
[normal]).
[normal]In many of these areas the 
[normal]marine aggregates 
[normal]sector is acknowledged as being a leader amongst the extractive industries and as a consequence
[normal] recognises a significantly improved relationship with many NGOs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question [bold]10[bold]:[bold] What is the competitive landscape for the extractive industries in the 21st Century and is it in the UK’s interest to remain a global centre for them?[bold]The competitive landsca
[normal]pe for the UK building materials industry has altered over the last decade following the acquisition of UK companies by global organisations for whom cement production is a core activity (e.g. – purchase of Hanson by Heidelberg Cement, RMC by Cemex, 
[normal]and Ag
[normal]gregate
[normal] Industries by Holcim).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This industry wide consolidation has led to greater integration of UK and European suppliers and competition for available capital investment. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The low value
[normal] of some minerals (e.g. aggregates) means that local markets remain a feature for 
[normal]most 
[normal]suppliers that do not have the ability to take advantage of rail or sea logistics. Marine minerals are in a position to take advantage of cro
[normal]ss
[normal] border trade, with around
[normal] 
[normal]a third
[normal] 
[normal]of marine aggregates and
[normal] half 
[normal]of potash supplies being exported.
[normal]We trust that you will find these comments 
[normal]helpful and 
[normal]constructive. 
[normal]We would be very willing to provide additional information on any of the points we have raised above
[normal] and be very pleased to discuss these matters with you further
[normal]. 
[normal]Through the 
[normal]Energy &amp; Infrastructure’s 
[normal]Minerals &amp; Infrastructure
[normal] team
[normal], w
[normal]e are ready to engage in further discussions on these and other points relevant to our ownership or which our expertise m
[normal]ay be brought to bear.
[normal] All of this response may be put into the public domain and there is no part of it that should be treated as confidential.
